
[1]duplicity

   DUPLICITY, n. [L., double.]

   1. Doubleness; the number two.

   2. Doubleness of heart or speech; the act or practice of exhibiting a
   different or contrary conduct, or uttering different or contrary
   sentiments, at different times, in relation to the same thing; or the
   act of dissembling ones real opinions for the purpose of concealing
   them and misleading persons in the conversation and intercourse of
   life; double-dealing; dissimulation; deceit.

   3. In law, duplicity is the pleading of two or more distinct matters or
   single pleas.
